SOB 12 - Microcontroller Behaviour and Data Processing

Objective: Upload a program to an Arduino and describe how the microcontroller processes data
and how the physical device behaves.

Program Used

An Arduino program was uploaded to control an LED using PWM (Pulse Width Modulation).
The LED gradually increased and decreased in brightness.

How the Microcontroller Processes Data

When powered on, the Arduino executes the setup function once and configures the LED pin as an output.
The loop function then runs continuously. Brightness values between 0 and 255 are processed by the microcontroller
and sent to the LED using PWM, controlling the amount of power delivered to the LED.

Observed Physical Behaviour

After uploading the program, the LED started in the OFF state.
It gradually became brighter until it reached maximum brightness and then gradually became dimmer until it turned OFF again.
This process repeated continuously.

Comparison of Expected and Actual Behaviour

Expected Behaviour             | Actual Behaviour

LED fades on and off smoothly. | LED faded on and off smoothly.

Conclusion

The microcontroller successfully processed brightness values and controlled the LED as expected.
The observed physical behaviour matched the intended behaviour of the program,
confirming that the code was uploaded correctly and the device operated as designed.